The first virtual operator is already arriving, this year, in the Czech Republic.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer almost all the services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not going to take long to arrive.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>TU) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming rates it is likely to come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS that they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that you really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very hard to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market that brought a prominent price drop to which the classic operators had to react as well.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for these types of operators and that they can succeed.
There is no need to look for examples far too far.
In February of this year we inform you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only half a year later, this operator managed to get more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they are enough with far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not bear relatively high costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are usually profiled at low cost – they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that, however, are often countered by the offer of more tailored services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half of the cheap compared to the competition.
However, as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland can also be a good blow to bet on a nothing trivial target group.
This operator is directed specifically to the man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator he likes and who he can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works for this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as Poland could encroach on our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the service offering is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
“We’re talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it doesn’t seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region,” Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, said in a telephone conversation for mobile.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, they try to do their best to avoid any potential competition.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Nowera group who would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
“We have a great interest in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile phone services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility, we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have been able to move forward in the meetings," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe there are better times.
It seems that, by informal information, the first official operator would probably have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment, we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market refers to other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional compliance with O2’s opinion, adds: “Until now we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop.”
“On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find a virtual operator by the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study in such a short time."
Vodafone focuses on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of the cost and infrastructure distribution.
We consider it to be the biggest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is to partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on mobile.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a fall in prices and thereby a fall in profits.
So why make it easier to enter the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of that is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>TU was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is confirmed by the public information available on the <0xC4><0x8C>TU website.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: “In addition, it has not been long since the competitive environment in the mobile market was opened to a fourth operator.
With regard to the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his services, great demands."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in trade tenders, unlike the UK and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Trade Tenders (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, she expressed her typical stance on this issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after a lease agreement on the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
To date, no agreement has been concluded since the offer of the potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for the classic operators,” added Kristián Chalupa, from the Department of Foreign Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS, to our question.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from that, they must note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Particularly when Kristián Chalupa adds: “In abroad where virtual operators operate normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in prices of mobile phone services”
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the price drop are not in the interest of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
The truly dramatically shocking thing in this case lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it is really a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in gas stations as it is clear that it is the work of chance and of a fierce struggle for competition.
"The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position therefore do not have a corresponding increase in liability in their market performance.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as are telecommunications regulators,” Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many conflicting points.
Obviously, there is a relevant market analysis drawn up by the <0xC4><0x8C>TU that telecommunications are a single market from the point of view of the commercial tender.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech traders have a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge is always necessary the agreement with the network administrator.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS should represent a warning that three mobile operators are ascending in a similar way.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that in all negotiations with the operators they collide with many similar obstacles.
Loading responsibility in the <0xC4><0x8C>TU is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications, of which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes hands in all this matter.
We have already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act for the expansion of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU’s competence in the field of non-effective trade tenders was recently introduced, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
<0xC3><0x9A>OHS representatives should know this perfectly, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
Everything is fine, when no one looks
At the same time, something like a pseudovirtual operator still works unnoticed that in Czech mobile networks already exist a few.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, are only a part of the public.
These are usually companies that are dedicated to multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few chosen get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the same by ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the trade conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
“If cases such as those cited could be found, there could be a violation of the terms of the contract which could be translated into the end of the collaboration with the given society,” Martina Kemrová answered the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach people responsible.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned above that it can reach thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they get nothing negligible profits and, at the same time – unlike authentic virtual operators – in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns us of possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a demeaningly large percentage of customers.
These, in addition, must accept that your phone’s SIM card is not in your name so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of the operators.”
This is exactly what the <0xC4><0x8C>TU should look like a little bit strange.
There is also a new question for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators surround the eyes in this type of procedure, why block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it should not be content with the operators’ explanations that they have no idea of this story and that their trading conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As has already been made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market brought a significant drop in service prices.
At the same time, in virtually every country where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried to protect themselves more or less from this breakthrough.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with service quality, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have intervened at this time and in no case have defended the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to emerge the first virtual operator and with it began to emerge more.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all of this case happens as if it were a burning nail.
In our experience, we can not fail to impress that the confusion of assignments in these cases suits them.
But we will not despair.
If this background information is correct and the virtual operator really gets to these lands, then the Czech mobile market is likely to start moving again.
If one of the operators lets a virtual mobile operator enter, it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
