Rats also have feelings.
It is said that a rat or a cockroach feeling the danger is fleeing, why is it also afraid?
Joseph Le Doux, a scientist in the field of neurology, is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
How can they be controlled if they, acting in the same way as us, feel the same?
In an internet magazine called "Edge" for many years, the contributions of famous scientists are published.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series the chosen answers to the question What do you think is true without being able to prove it?
I think animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it until now, although we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case at least we can expect it because all human brains have the same fundamental configuration.
But as soon as we dedicate ourselves to other species and include questions about feeling and consciousness in general, we enter the unknown realm because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as other animals: it kills, escapes or attacks.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists draw conclusions about comparable subjective experience.
Of course I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to infect our subjective experience with that of animals.
First, they almost always include the circuits associated with the human consciousness of the lateral prefrontal lobe of the brain cortex (due to its participation in short memory and the executive functions that lead behavior).
This large part is much more developed in the case of humans than that of other primates and seems to be lacking absolutely in other creatures.
Given at least the aspects referred to our consciousness that depends on the prefrontal lobe of the brain cortex, including knowledge about who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is a reason to assume that even man differs from other primates.
Another particularity lies in the linguistic nature of man: Because most of his experience is linked to language, that often means that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
