Speaking of Sleeping
Some kids talk at night.
I’m not talking about those who wake up very spaciously telling us something that happened the day before, but about children who talk when they’re asleep.
The first time it happens best you get a scare, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somniloches.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told that he talked overnight.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life for example associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis, or sleepwalking, but it doesn’t have to be that way.
As we mentioned above they may also be associated with very high fever pictures, stress or overexcitation situations.
However, it is an unstudied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a whisper or the opposite (creams, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any question that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him out this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (e.g., if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid TV shows or series that are frightening or a bit violent.
With very nervous children and who have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the dreamloches appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even though he's talking, he's sleeping and therefore he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes it would be advisable to consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common), don’t fall into the temptation to question him for information.
You won’t get anything, because when you’re asleep, you’re not conscious enough to organize your thinking.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming of saying that, with which you are very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can question him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing bad, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
