The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec was celebrating its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to be delighted, because Hema-Québec has been once again one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence that had been seriously hesitated by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and Hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which aimed to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster could not be repeated.
While Judge Krever was delayed in presenting his relationship, certain provinces then set up a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Society with blood to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38 percent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalls Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence,” he says before proudly affirming that in early 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we witnessed in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of the mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, that when we do not know it and when a serious disease can emanate from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, we put in place measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven undoubtedly that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow donors to detect the presence of the virus directly in the blood and not anti-virus antibodies, in which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleic acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We could reduce this period by less than a week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements significantly lowered the risk of contracting AIDS by a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“That means there will be 12 million blood products to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission occurs for a blood product.
I think it is now possible to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without worries,” said the head of Hema-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, for example, the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant,” says Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Hema-Québec should also provide sufficient supply.
"Necessities are increasing because the population is aging.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the blood donor network that, on average, regroups only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.
All people with good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria can nevertheless donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Poverty is very rare.
But members of this donor network need to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain it and encourage it to be a regular donor.
Since current life is very unbroken, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating her blood,” Francine Décary says.
With a budget of <0x24>297 million annually, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting on the bank our thousandth sample of blood from the umbilical cord and is expected to take out more than a thousand of these each year.
We should start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary describing this cord blood sample program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed that they can't enjoy this " as Hema-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
