Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice President and Director of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
According to Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the world’s largest gold company attempted a six-million-euro defamation trial against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a “transparent public debate”.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of persecution for defamation, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, the best way to hold a public debate would be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to theirs?
The outcome of the dispute is of little importance, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and fight, with very uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers held by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly arrangement that will amortize the opposition as well as scare anyone who dares to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it was in front of the public that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by change of mind and not by whistleblowers.
It was therefore sufficient for the miners to open their books, records and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent search teams that could have clarified the matter.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he could ask for a "public" debate, disregarding the opinions of the latter?
According to the Vice-President, this word seems to refer only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What he doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - Barrick Gold, is that the audience that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so above all because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but based on civilized changes of arguments, and not within what many people perceive as a persecution-murder (seeing the "public debate," Barrick Gold has just filed a claim with respect to the authors of Noir Canada that they do not use this word more intimately).
In addition to Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the Barrick Gold process is a direct attack on the freedom of university search and the truth, essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and debate facts and interpretations, which are the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the wealthy businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under many persecutions, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s unscrupulous persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he claims, he does not want to have a transparent debate.
It’s a loss for the university world, but also for public debate in Canada, and it’s time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
