Psychology of Overlaps: Why We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
New York University neurologists and economists have discovered the neurological-economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in Science magazine, people don’t want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists attempted to establish the neurological scheme of this “game” through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, the other participated in an auction and while it was examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (fMRI) the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games participants could earn money, but during auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, as the loss of the game intensified the operation of the complex called stratum located below the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the “self-reward” mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention not to provoke an intense stratum reaction.
To base their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups wagered against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive <0x24>15 more prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly <0x24>15 before the auction, but in the event of losing the auction the members of the group even lost that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one, triumph was highlighted and for the other, failure.
However, checking the neurologists’ hypothesis, the members of the group that played “against failure” were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the “winning” group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For so far, they explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped solve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to go to the doctor?
Around 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the patients do not know they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name for various diseases of the liver caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; they are characteristic of liver infection and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humors (sperm, vaginal humor, saliva).
Travelers are advised to protect themselves with a vaccine against viruses A and B, against C, there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, it manifests itself by means of a general malady, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that appear on the skin and in the white of the eyes the jaundice, the excretion becomes clear, dark-colored urine and healing can last up to two - three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are ill because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Therefore, premature recognition, systematic medical control, is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and those who wear tattoos.
Today there are about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory checkup as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptom.
The disease has healing if it is discovered in time, it is possible to eradicate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its goal is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less to those who believe in God?
According to a recent research, religious faith has a calming effect that also relieved the deaths of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed how religious belief influences human pain, reports the British newspaper Telegraph.
As part of this unique experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first of the series of research in which besides academics also participate scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University.
The analysis took place as follows; they fixed a sparkling instrument to the left hand of the patient, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at it in two paintings: the Virgin Mary, a 17th-century work of Sassoferrato and the 15th-century Lady of the armor of Leonardo da Vinci.
The researchers hoped that the show of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a soothing effect.
Patients spent half an hour on an MRI scan, receiving 20 electrical shocks in four consecutive parts during observation of religious theme painting or the other.
The Catholics stated that when looking at the Virgin Mary they felt in “security” as people “protected,” “they calmed themselves and peace reigned in their hearts.”
By observing the religious theme picture they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so striking you can get a similar effect with atheists as well, you just have to find the right image.
“We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the result of the investigation.
“The exercise of faith should and in many cases really change our personality,” Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of his size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
