The smart car mimics the flight of the beehive
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of existing obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, the beekeepers.
In a surprising project presented at the CEATEC of Japan, beekeepers gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic steering system of nature-like BR23C cars, which were given the characteristics of beehives, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight, each beehive creates its own private oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained at the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, RP Technology Director and Development and Research.
Composite eyes of bees play an important role that are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of compound eyes, the engineers used the laser-length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at a 180 degree angle, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot imitating the movements of the beehives, changes the direction by rotating the wheels to the extent necessary.
Unlike any current system, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If not, the vehicle robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process should be carried out in one open and close eyes.
However, unlike bees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be bidimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the beekeepers to avoid other beekeepers, here they only used as a possibility for the auto robot the rotary movement and the acceleration in addition to the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is higher, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the ability to process data, not much less that of storage.
This apparatus in every second should only process some input signals and react according to the case.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so only uses a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No gigabyte or megabyte memory is required.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately bypass the obstacles, which according to Nissan’s calculations, can be incorporated into mass-produced models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, bypassing the existing obstacles on his way.
