Industrial Prices Continue to Rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices rose by 0.1 percent compared to last month’s prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007’s prices – the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent from those of July 2008 and fell by 3.9 per cent from those of the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent from the previous month and by 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices rose only to a minimum, with 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry increased minimally, by 0.1 percent compared to the month of July.
The biggest increase in price volume occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), primarily due to an increase of 4.6 per cent per month in bags and belts and an increase of 2.5 per cent in footwear.
The highest price level for plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the price of the chemicals production branch (1.6 per cent).
Price drops occurred in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing houses and printing houses did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water representing a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, primarily as a result of the effect of the official price increase from July 1.
In a 12-month comparison - in the domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metal manufacturing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
Prices decreased in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
Over the past year, global prices in the processing industry increased by 10.2 percent.
Electricity, gas, heat and water prices exceeded prices for the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while prices in the energy sector and the intermediate sectors did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sector and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
In consumer goods-producing branches, there was a 6.8 per cent decline and in investment goods a 1.4 per cent decline.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 per cent.
The valuation of our national currency in one month decreased by 1.7 percent with respect to the euro and by 7.1 percent with respect to the dollar, up by 7.5 percent with respect to the euro and 15.9 percent with respect to the dollar compared to August 2007.
