Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has begun in Paris, its host is France, which this year is also the European Union’s vice-president.
Lívia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party for Fidesz, in her message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that hit gypsy children and is also the biggest obstacle to their attention.
This high-level conference was inaugurated - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for employment, social affairs and equal opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European social rights organisations.
Jároka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of deputies in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Gypsies remain out of the labour market in the first place due to their low level of schooling.
“Most young Gypsies have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a small part can get a university degree.”
Jároka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, plays a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investing in the education of gypsy children at an early age can strengthen the economies of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise a broad awareness of these issues both among Gypsies and among non-Gypsies.
For the earlier a Gypsy student starts school, the more likely they will be to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
“Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education,” said Lívia Jároka.
According to the MEP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to immediately accelerate the processes of school deprivation, for which proper compliance with existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is of fundamental importance.
“We have to break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we have to offer Roma children the possibility of ensuring a democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as citizens with full rights,” Jároka said.
The European Summit on Equal Opportunities, held annually since last year's Berlin meeting, which was held on the occasion of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities", is aimed at ensuring a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level.
