Farewell to old cinema Paradise, cities cancel historic halls
Historic cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers and also in the province cities.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticulous in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of monkey rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
Almost always disappearing are historical places, full of memory,"it's like a friend dies, a friend with whom a piece of place and so much excitement was shared," observes the director of the new movie Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago always won the Oscar-winning cousin and the grand prize of the jury in Cannes.
The figures given by Anec, the main trader’s association, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and to pay the most are mainly the halls of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures are Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas less, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the event of the multiplex is responsible for its disappearance, it is these three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new meticulous cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec,” it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to move to the meticulous.
Not to mention the lack of funds for traders: the state’s previous debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector it would need between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interestingly, the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to be concerned about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono sala both in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the rules envisaged, there are mediums of tax facilitation in favour of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special parking fees.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” observes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true that to contrast the extra power of the meticulous, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a subject that was always important to me: the closure of Bagheria cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to perform the "New Paradise cinema", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the already closed Via Nazionale Quirinale, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.
